Join Concepts
INNER JOIN
Returns only matching rows from both tables. Example use case: employees who are assigned to a department.
LEFT OUTER JOIN
Returns all rows from the left table and matching rows from the right table. If no match exists, right-side columns show NULL. Example use case: all employees, including those not assigned to any department.
RIGHT OUTER JOIN
Returns all rows from the right table and matching rows from the left table. Example use case: all departments, including departments without matching employee details.
FULL OUTER JOIN
Returns all rows from both tables. Matching rows are combined; non-matching rows from either side show NULL.
CROSS JOIN
Returns every possible combination of rows between two tables. Example use case: pairing every employee with every department for planning or simulation.
SELF JOIN
Joins a table with itself. Your current employee table does not have a manager_id, so self joins can be practiced using comparisons like salary, hire date, or job title.
NATURAL JOIN
Automatically joins tables using columns with the same name. In your schema, both tables have employee_id, so Oracle can naturally join them.
JOIN USING
Joins tables using a shared column name, such as employee_id.
JOIN ON
The most flexible join syntax. You manually specify the join condition.
NON-EQUI JOIN
Uses conditions other than =, such as >, <, BETWEEN, etc. Example: compare employees by salary ranges or hire dates.
ANTI JOIN Pattern
Finds records in one table that do not have a match in another table, usually using LEFT JOIN ... WHERE right_column IS NULL.
SEMI JOIN Pattern
Finds rows from one table that have at least one matching row in another table, usually using EXISTS or IN.
